{"title_page": "Philip Hill-Pearson", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Philip Hill-Pearson\n| image                   =\n| birth_name               =\n| birth_date               = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1987|06|16}}\n| birth_place              = [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8002275.performers-hit-the-high-notes-asfestival-proves-to-be-a-big-success/|title=Performers hit the high notes as festival proves to be a big success|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| occupation              = Actor\n| yearsactive             = 2010\u2013present\n| spouse                =\n}}\n\n'''Philip Hill-Pearson''' is a British [[actor]]. He trained at [[East 15 Acting School]], graduating in 2009.<ref>[https://voiceovers.mandy.com/uk/voice-artist/profile/philip-hill-pearson \"CCP resume for Philip Hill Pearson, showing credits and training\"] ''MandyVoices'' Retrieved 24 January 2016</ref> Shortly after graduating from the drama school, he was cast as [[List of Shameless (British TV series) characters#Bruce Donnelly|Bruce Donnelly]] in the comedy drama series ''[[Shameless (British TV series)|Shameless]]''. Following on from this, he went on to work in a range of differing television programs, including ''[[Good Cop]]'' and ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'', and also films such as ''[[United (2011 film)|United]]'', with [[David Tennant]],<ref>[http://heyjupiter.co.uk/sundance-channel-to-exclusively-premiere-acclaimed-drama-united-starring-david-tennant-on-13-september/ \"Sundance Channel will present the exclusive premiere of the acclaimed feature-length television drama United \"] ''Hey Jupiter Communications'' Retrieved 30 January 2016</ref> and [[Steven Spielberg]]'s adaptation of [[Michael Morpurgo]]'s [[War Horse (film)|War Horse]].<ref>[http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8442025.Philip_goes_to_war_with_Spielberg/ \"Clayton actor gets to experience life in the trenches\"] ''The Telegraph & Argus'' Retrieved 30 January 2016</ref> Alongside his extensive work in British film and television, Pearson also worked with the [[Hull Truck Theatre]] on their stage production of [[The Rise and Fall of Little Voice]] in 2011, playing the role of Billy.<ref>[http://www.hull.co.uk/news.asp?PageID=74&MediaCategoryID=3&NewsID=1979&MediaType=news \"Article on 'The Rise and Fall of Little Voice', Hull Truck Theatre\"] ''News From Business Across Hull & Humber'' Retrieved 30 January 2016</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[United (2011 film)|United]]''\n| Eddie Colman\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[War Horse (film)|War Horse]]''\n| Wounded Soldier\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Shameless (British TV series)|Shameless]]''\n| [[List of Shameless (British TV series) characters#Bruce Donnelly|Bruce Donnelly]]\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Good Cop]]''\n| DC Liam Frainey\n| \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[WPC 56]]''\n| Frank Marshall\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Common (film)|Common]]''\n| Tony\n| TV Film\n|-\n| 2013-2015\n| ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''\n| Jay Scagell / Norman Wattle\n| 3 episodes (2 in 2013 and 1 in 2015)\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[No Offence]]''\n| Jimmy Webb\n| \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]''\n| Lee Stonnall\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n| DC Hough\n| Recurring role\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|3807052}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hill-Pearson, Philip}}\n[[Category:21st-century British male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male film actors]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Philip Hill-Pearson\n| image                   =\n| birth_name               =\n| birth_date               = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1987|06|16}}\n| birth_place              = [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| occupation              = Actor\n| yearsactive             = 2010\u2013present\n| spouse                =\n}}\n\n'''Philip Hill-Pearson''' is a British [[actor]]. He trained at [[East 15 Acting School]], graduating in 2009.<ref>[https://voiceovers.mandy.com/uk/voice-artist/profile/philip-hill-pearson \"CCP resume for Philip Hill Pearson, showing credits and training\"] ''MandyVoices'' Retrieved 24 January 2016</ref> Shortly after graduating from the drama school, he was cast as [[List of Shameless (British TV series) characters#Bruce Donnelly|Bruce Donnelly]] in the comedy drama series ''[[Shameless (British TV series)|Shameless]]''. Following on from this, he went on to work in a range of differing television programs, including ''[[Good Cop]]'' and ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'', and also films such as ''[[United (2011 film)|United]]'', with [[David Tennant]],<ref>[http://heyjupiter.co.uk/sundance-channel-to-exclusively-premiere-acclaimed-drama-united-starring-david-tennant-on-13-september/ \"Sundance Channel will present the exclusive premiere of the acclaimed feature-length television drama United \"] ''Hey Jupiter Communications'' Retrieved 30 January 2016</ref> and [[Steven Spielberg]]'s adaptation of [[Michael Morpurgo]]'s [[War Horse (film)|War Horse]].<ref>[http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8442025.Philip_goes_to_war_with_Spielberg/ \"Clayton actor gets to experience life in the trenches\"] ''The Telegraph & Argus'' Retrieved 30 January 2016</ref> Alongside his extensive work in British film and television, Pearson also worked with the [[Hull Truck Theatre]] on their stage production of [[The Rise and Fall of Little Voice]] in 2011, playing the role of Billy.<ref>[http://www.hull.co.uk/news.asp?PageID=74&MediaCategoryID=3&NewsID=1979&MediaType=news \"Article on 'The Rise and Fall of Little Voice', Hull Truck Theatre\"] ''News From Business Across Hull & Humber'' Retrieved 30 January 2016</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[United (2011 film)|United]]''\n| Eddie Colman\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[War Horse (film)|War Horse]]''\n| Wounded Soldier\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Shameless (British TV series)|Shameless]]''\n| [[List of Shameless (British TV series) characters#Bruce Donnelly|Bruce Donnelly]]\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Good Cop]]''\n| DC Liam Frainey\n| \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[WPC 56]]''\n| Frank Marshall\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Common (film)|Common]]''\n| Tony\n| TV Film\n|-\n| 2013-2015\n| ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''\n| Jay Scagell / Norman Wattle\n| 3 episodes (2 in 2013 and 1 in 2015)\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[No Offence]]''\n| Jimmy Webb\n| \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]''\n| Lee Stonnall\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n| DC Hough\n| Recurring role\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|3807052}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hill-Pearson, Philip}}\n[[Category:21st-century British male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male film actors]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Danstarr69", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Hill-Pearson"}
{"title_page": "Antony Gough", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date= February 2020}}\n[[File:ShandsEmporium gobeirne.jpg|thumb|Gough gave [[Shand's Emporium]], the oldest commercial building in the [[Christchurch Central City]], to a Christchurch heritage trust and it was relocated to Manchester Street]]\n'''Antony Thomas Gough''' (born 1949) is a New Zealand businessman and property developer based in [[Christchurch]]. The grandson of Tracy Thomas Gough, who founded Gough, Gough and Hamer,<ref name=\"family tree\">{{cite news |last=Steeman |first=Marta |title=Gough's sister 'won't sell' |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/business/9483628/Goughs-sister-won-t-sell |accessdate=18 December 2013 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=6 December 2013}}</ref> Gough is considered to be one of the city's most influential businessmen. He is the developer of The Terrace, a major commercial development in [[City Mall, Christchurch|Christchurch's retail district]] and part of the city's reconstruction programme following the [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|2011 earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/8402989/Christchurchs-Mr-Personality |title=Antony Gough \u2013 Mr Personality |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |date=9 March 2013 |accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/work-begins-major-christchurch-development-5587978 |title=Work begins on major Christchurch development |work=One News |publisher=TVNZ |date=20 September 2013 |accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nGough was educated at [[Christ's College, Christchurch|Christ's College]] from 1962 to 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christscollege.com/ccoba/membership-directory/1996-example-name |title=Membership directory |year=2016 |website= |publisher=Christ's College |accessdate=15 April 2016 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424045952/http://christscollege.com/ccoba/membership-directory/1996-example-name |archivedate=24 April 2016 }}</ref> He graduated from the [[University of Canterbury]] with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in 1970 with honours in nuclear science,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cairns |first1=Lois |title=Gough hailed for rebuild work |work=[[The Press]] |date=18 February 2014 |page=A10}}</ref> and was awarded an [[List of Honorary Doctors of the University of Canterbury|honorary doctorate]] in commerce in April 2014 from the same institution.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gough just chuffed with honorary doctorate |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/9946328/Gough-just-chuffed-with-honorary-doctorate |accessdate=19 April 2014 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=16 April 2014 |page=A4}}</ref> \n\nGough, his brothers Tracy Gough and Harcourt Gough, and his twin sister [[Avenal McKinnon]] are part-owners of Gough Holdings Ltd, previously known as Gough, Gough and Hamer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/business/90065521/high-court-decision-gough-holdings-power-passes-to-ben-gough-and-gina-satterthwaite|title=High Court decision: Gough Holdings power passes to Ben Gough and Gina Satterthwaite|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\"family tree\" /> The company supplies heavy equipment for the mining, forestry, transport and power industries in [[Australasia]] and employs 950 staff.<ref name=\"family tree\" />\n\nIn 2013, an attempt of the B T Gough Trust to obtain a controlling stake of Gough Holdings Ltd through gaining shareholding of the O T Gough Trust went to the [[High Court of New Zealand|High Court]].<ref name=\"family dispute\">{{cite news |last=Steeman |first=Marta |title=Gough family's 'bitter' dispute  |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/industries/9477888/Gough-familys-bitter-dispute |accessdate=18 December 2013 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=5 December 2013}}</ref> The ''[[National Business Review]]'' estimates the value of the Gough family at NZ$300m.<ref name=\"family dispute\" />\n\nThe Gough family owned [[Shand's Emporium]] in Hereford Street, the oldest commercial building in the [[Christchurch Central City]], from circa 1940. Gough sold the Category I [[New Zealand Historic Places Trust|heritage building]] for $1 as it was in the way of The Terrace development, and it was transported to a new site in Manchester Street.<ref name=\"Shands Emporium\">{{cite news |last=Stylianou |first=Georgina |title=Shands Emporium waits for new owner |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/8885594/Shands-Emporium-waits-for-new-owner |accessdate=18 December 2013 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=6 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NZHPT 307\">{{NZHPT|307|Shands Emporium|18 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cairns|first1=Lois|title=Historic Shand's Emporium bought for $1|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/69419405/historic-shands-emporium-bought-for-1.html|accessdate=13 April 2016|work=[[The Press]]|date=16 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Antony Gough}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Christchurch earthquakes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gough, Antony}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:University of Canterbury alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with the 2011 Christchurch earthquake]]\n[[Category:People educated at Christ's College, Christchurch]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date= February 2020}}\n[[File:ShandsEmporium gobeirne.jpg|thumb|Gough gave [[Shand's Emporium]], the oldest commercial building in the [[Christchurch Central City]], to a Christchurch heritage trust and it was relocated to Manchester Street]]\n'''Antony Thomas Gough''' (born 1949) is a New Zealand businessman and property developer based in [[Christchurch]]. The grandson of Tracy Thomas Gough, who founded Gough, Gough and Hamer,<ref name=\"family tree\">{{cite news |last=Steeman |first=Marta |title=Gough's sister 'won't sell' |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/business/9483628/Goughs-sister-won-t-sell |accessdate=18 December 2013 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=6 December 2013}}</ref> Gough is considered to be one of the city's most influential businessmen. He is the developer of The Terrace, a major commercial development in [[City Mall, Christchurch|Christchurch's retail district]] and part of the city's reconstruction programme following the [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|2011 earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/8402989/Christchurchs-Mr-Personality |title=Antony Gough - Mr Personality |publisher=Stuff.co.nz |date=9 March 2013 |accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/work-begins-major-christchurch-development-5587978 |title=Work begins on major Christchurch development |work=One News |publisher=TVNZ |date=20 September 2013 |accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nGough was educated at [[Christ's College, Christchurch|Christ's College]] from 1962 to 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christscollege.com/ccoba/membership-directory/1996-example-name |title=Membership directory |year=2016 |website= |publisher=Christ's College |accessdate=15 April 2016 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424045952/http://christscollege.com/ccoba/membership-directory/1996-example-name |archivedate=24 April 2016 }}</ref> He graduated from the [[University of Canterbury]] with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in 1970 with honours in nuclear science,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cairns |first1=Lois |title=Gough hailed for rebuild work |work=[[The Press]] |date=18 February 2014 |page=A10}}</ref> and was awarded an [[List of Honorary Doctors of the University of Canterbury|honorary doctorate]] in commerce in April 2014 from the same institution.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gough just chuffed with honorary doctorate |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/9946328/Gough-just-chuffed-with-honorary-doctorate |accessdate=19 April 2014 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=16 April 2014 |page=A4}}</ref> \n\nGough, his brothers Tracy Gough and Harcourt Gough, and his twin sister [[Avenal McKinnon]] are part-owners of Gough Holdings Ltd, previously known as Gough, Gough and Hamer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/business/90065521/high-court-decision-gough-holdings-power-passes-to-ben-gough-and-gina-satterthwaite|title=High Court decision: Gough Holdings power passes to Ben Gough and Gina Satterthwaite|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\"family tree\" /> The company supplies heavy equipment for the mining, forestry, transport and power industries in [[Australasia]] and employs 950 staff.<ref name=\"family tree\" />\n\nIn 2013, an attempt of the B T Gough Trust to obtain a controlling stake of Gough Holdings Ltd through gaining shareholding of the O T Gough Trust went to the [[High Court of New Zealand|High Court]].<ref name=\"family dispute\">{{cite news |last=Steeman |first=Marta |title=Gough family's 'bitter' dispute  |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/industries/9477888/Gough-familys-bitter-dispute |accessdate=18 December 2013 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=5 December 2013}}</ref> The ''[[National Business Review]]'' estimates the value of the Gough family at NZ$300m.<ref name=\"family dispute\" />\n\nThe Gough family owned [[Shand's Emporium]] in Hereford Street, the oldest commercial building in the [[Christchurch Central City]], from circa 1940. Gough sold the Category I [[New Zealand Historic Places Trust|heritage building]] for $1 as it was in the way of The Terrace development, and it was transported to a new site in Manchester Street.<ref name=\"Shands Emporium\">{{cite news |last=Stylianou |first=Georgina |title=Shands Emporium waits for new owner |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/8885594/Shands-Emporium-waits-for-new-owner |accessdate=18 December 2013 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=6 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NZHPT 307\">{{NZHPT|307|Shands Emporium|18 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cairns|first1=Lois|title=Historic Shand's Emporium bought for $1|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/69419405/historic-shands-emporium-bought-for-1.html|accessdate=13 April 2016|work=[[The Press]]|date=16 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Antony Gough}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Christchurch earthquakes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gough, Antony}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:University of Canterbury alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with the 2011 Christchurch earthquake]]\n[[Category:People educated at Christ's College, Christchurch]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antony_Gough"}
