{"title_page": "Tokyo Godfathers", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name          = Tokyo Godfathers\n| image         = Tokyo Godfathers (Movie Poster).jpg\n| caption       = Theatrical release poster\n| director      = [[Satoshi Kon]]\n| producer      = {{Plain list|\n* Shinichi Kobayashi\n* [[Masao Takiyama]]\n* Taro Maki\n}}\n| screenplay    = {{Plain list|\n* [[Keiko Nobumoto]]\n* Satoshi Kon\n}}\n| story         = Satoshi Kon\n| starring      = {{Plain list|\n* [[T\u014dru Emori]]\n* Yoshiaki Umegaki\n* [[Aya Okamoto]]\n}}\n| music         = {{Plain list|\n* [[Keiichi Suzuki (composer)|Keiichi Suzuki]]\n* Moonriders\n}}\n| cinematography = Katsutoshi Sugai\n| editing       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Takeshi Seyama]]\n* Kashiko Kimura\n}}\n| studio        = [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse]]\n| distributor   = [[Sony Pictures Entertainment Japan]]\n| released      = {{Film date|2003|08|30|[[Big Apple Anime Fest]]|2003|11|08|Japan}}\n| runtime       = 92 minutes\n| country       = Japan\n| language      = Japanese\n| budget        = $2.4 million<ref name=\"InterCatsuka\">{{cite web |title=Interview Satoshi Kon |language=French |url=http://www.catsuka.com/focuson.php?id=itw_satoshikon |publisher=Catsuka |date=October 18, 2006 |accessdate=December 20, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross         = $847,106<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web|title=Tokyo Godfathers (2004) - Financial Information |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Tokyo-Godfathers#tab=summary |publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''Tokyo Godfathers'''''|\u6771\u4eac\u30b4\u30c3\u30c9\u30d5\u30a1\u30fc\u30b6\u30fc\u30ba|T\u014dky\u014d Goddof\u0101z\u0101zu}} is a 2003 Japanese [[anime]] holiday, [[Adventure film|adventure]], [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[Satoshi Kon]] loosely based on [[Peter B. Kyne]]'s novel ''[[The Three Godfathers (novel)|Three Godfathers]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hunt|first1=Leon|title=Tauris World Cinema : East Asian Cinemas : Exploring Transnational Connections on Film|date=2010|publisher=I.B Tauris|isbn=9781845116149|pages=122}}</ref>\n\n''Tokyo Godfathers'' was the third animated film directed by Kon and the second which he both wrote and directed. [[Keiko Nobumoto]], noted for being the creator of the ''[[Wolf's Rain]]'' series and a head scriptwriter for ''[[Cowboy Bebop]]'', co-wrote the script with Kon.\n\n''Tokyo Godfathers'' received an Excellence Prize at the 2003 [[Japan Media Arts Festival]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://archive.j-mediaarts.jp/en/festival/2003/animation/works/07an_TOKYO_GOD_FATHERS | title=Excellence Award - TOKYO GOD FATHERS {{!}} Award {{!}} Animation Division {{!}} 2003 [7th] {{!}} Japan Media Arts Festival Archive}}</ref> It also won [[Mainichi Film Award for Best Animation Film|Best Animation Film]] at the 58th [[Mainichi Film Awards]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kon|first=Satoshi|title=The Art of Satoshi Kon|publisher=|others=Tribute from Darren Aronofsky|year=2015|isbn=978-1-61655-741-6|edition=First|location=Milwaukie, OR|pages=142|oclc=896980881}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/mfa/history/058.html|title=\u6bce\u65e5\u6620\u753b\u30b3\u30f3\u30af\u30fc\u30eb \u7b2c58\u56de\uff082003\u5e74\uff09|website=\u6bce\u65e5\u65b0\u805e|language=ja|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nOne Christmas Eve after watching a children's performance of the [[Nativity scene]], three [[Homelessness|homeless]] people \u2013 a middle-aged alcoholic named Gin, a former [[transgender]] [[drag queen]] named Hana, and a dependent teenage [[Runaway (dependent)|runaway]] girl named Miyuki \u2013 discover an abandoned newborn while searching through the garbage. Deposited with the unnamed baby is a note asking the unknown finder to take good care of her and a bag containing clues to the parents' identity. The trio sets out to find the baby's parents. The baby is named {{nihongo|Kiyoko|\u6e05\u5b50}} by Hana, based on the Japanese translation of ''[[Silent Night]]'' literally meaning \"pure child\", as she is found on [[Christmas Eve]]. \n\nOutside a [[cemetery]], the group encounters a high-ranking [[yakuza]] boss trapped under his car. The man happens to know the owner of the club where Kiyoko's mother used to work; his daughter is going to be marrying the club's owner that day. At the wedding reception, the groom tells them that the baby's mother is a former bar girl named Sachiko. He gives them Sachiko's address, but the party is interrupted when a maid, revealed to be a Latin American [[Contract killing|hitman]] in disguise, attempts to shoot the bride's father. The hitman kidnaps Miyuki and baby Kiyoko while holding them hostage at gunpoint and takes them back to his home. There, Miyuki befriends the hitman's wife-(who also has a baby of her own) and shows her some pictures of her family.\n\nHana searches for Miyuki and Kiyoko while Gin takes care of an elderly homeless man who is dying in the street. After giving Gin a little red bag, the old man peacefully passes away. Some teenagers show up and beat up Gin and the dead old man's corpse. Meanwhile, Hana finds the girls and they go off to find a place to stay.\n\nThey go to Angel Tower, Hana's former club where the latter used to work until Hana got fired for attacking an intoxicated customer for insulting her. Gin, who was rescued by another member of the club, is also there. The trio sets out to find Sachiko's house, but they discover that it has been torn down. They are informed of the unhappy relationship between Sachiko and her husband, who is a gambling alcoholic. The group rests at a store until they are told to leave by the clerk. Hana collapses, and is taken by Gin and Miyuki to the hospital. Once at the hospital, Gin finds his estranged daughter, who is also named Kiyoko, working as a nurse. Hana berates Gin in front of his daughter and storms out of the hospital, with Miyuki following behind with baby Kiyoko in hand.\n\nHana and Miyuki find Sachiko about to jump off a bridge. Sachiko insists that her husband got rid of the baby without her knowledge, and that they return the baby to her. Meanwhile, Gin finds Sachiko's husband, who confirms a TV report Gin saw earlier that Kiyoko was actually stolen by Sachiko from the hospital. They chase after Sachiko and Kiyoko. After an intense car chase, Miyuki chases Sachiko to the top of a building. Sachiko reveals she became pregnant in hopes it would bring her closer to her husband. When her baby was [[Stillbirth|stillborn]], she decided to kidnap Kiyoko from the hospital's nursery, thinking, in her grief, the baby was hers. As Sachiko is about to jump off the building intending to commit suicide with Kiyoko in her hands, her husband comes out of his apartment, located just across the street, and begs her to start over with him. Sachiko jumps off nevertheless, but Miyuki manages to catch her before she falls, but then Sachiko accidentally drops Kiyoko. Hana jumps off the building after Kiyoko, catches the baby, and lands safely due to a miraculous gust of wind.\n\nHana, Miyuki, and Gin are taken to the hospital. Miyuki hands Gin his cigarettes and drops the old man's small red bag on the floor, revealing a winning [[lottery]] ticket. Kiyoko's real parents want to ask the trio to become her godparents. When a police inspector introduces them to the trio, the inspector is revealed to be Miyuki's father.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[T\u014dru Emori]] (Japanese) and Jon Avner (English)<ref name=\"engdub\">{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-13/gkids-announces-new-english-dub-cast-for-satoshi-kon-tokyo-godfathers-film/.156415|title=GKIDS Announces New English Dub Cast for Satoshi Kon's Tokyo Godfathers Film|last=Sherman|first=Jennifer|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 13, 2020|work=[[Anime News Network]]}}</ref>{{efn|name=animaxdub|In the [[Animax Asia]] release of the film, Gin is voiced by Darren Pleavin, Hana by Russel Wait, and Miyuki by Candice Moore.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/movies/Tokyo-Godfathers/|title=Tokyo Godfathers|website=Behind The Voice Actors|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref>}} as {{nihongo|Gin|\u30ae\u30f3}}; a gambling addict and former bicycle shop owner who claims to have been a bicycle racer. He ran away from his family when his debts became too great. His daughter, a nurse, shares the name of the newfound baby Kiyoko.\n* Yoshiaki Umegaki (Japanese) and [[Shakina Nayfack]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" />{{efn|name=animaxdub}} as {{nihongo|Hana|\u30cf\u30ca}}; a former drag queen who became homeless following the death of a former boyfriend. Hana was also an abandoned child, and is the most sympathetic to Kiyoko's plight and is the one who gives the baby her name.\n* [[Aya Okamoto]] (Japanese) and Victoria Grace (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" />{{efn|name=animaxdub}} as {{nihongo|Miyuki|\u30df\u30e6\u30ad}}; a runaway high school student who fled home following a violent argument with her father.\n*[[Satomi Koorogi]] (Japanese) and [[Kari Wahlgren]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" />{{efn|name=animaxdub}}  as {{nihongo|Kiyoko|\u6e05\u5b50}} an abandoned infant girl that the main characters find in the dumpster on Christmas Eve and decide to reunite her with her parents.\n* [[Sh\u014dz\u014d Iizuka]] (Japanese) and [[Jamieson Price]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as {{nihongo|\u014cta|\u592a\u7530}}; a yakuza boss who the main characters save from being crushed by his car. In gratitude, he invites them to his daughter's wedding reception.\n* [[Seiz\u014d Kat\u014d]] (Japanese) and [[Kate Bornstein]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as {{nihongo|Mother|\u6bcd\u3055\u3093|Kaa-san}}; the proprietor of the [[gay bar]] Hana was formerly employed in.\n* [[Hiroya Ishimaru]] (Japanese) and [[Kirk Thornton]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as {{nihongo|Yasuo|\u6cf0\u7537}}; Sachiko's husband and the one who left Kiyoko at the garbage dump.\n* [[Ry\u016bji Saikachi]] (Japanese) and David Manis (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as an old homeless man who is discovered by Gin. He entrusts Gin with the disposal of a small red bag before passing away.\n* [[Y\u016bsaku Yara]] (Japanese) and [[Crispin Freeman]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as Miyuki's father; a policeman in charge of searching for the missing baby Kiyoko, who was separated from her family.\n* [[Ky\u014dko Terase]] as {{nihongo|Sachiko|\u5e78\u5b50}}; a woman who claims to be Kiyoko's mother.\n* [[Mamiko Noto]] as Gin's daughter; a nurse who is also named Kiyoko.\n* [[Satomi K\u014drogi]] as the daughter of the yakuza boss \u014cta, who is also named Kiyoko. \n* [[Akio \u014ctsuka]] as a doctor engaged to Gin's daughter Kiyoko.\n* [[Rikiya Koyama]] as {{nihongo|Arao|\u65b0\u90ce}}; \u014cta's son-in-law who was collecting debt from Gin.\n* [[Inuko Inuyama]] as {{nihongo|Kurumizawa|\u80e1\u6843\u6ca2}}; a resident of Sachiko's former neighborhood.\n* Kanako Yahara as {{nihongo|Yaman\u014dchi|\u5c71\u4e4b\u5185}}\n* Rie Shibata as {{nihongo|Nekobaba|\u732b\u30d0\u30d0}}\n* [[K\u014dichi Yamadera]] as Taxi driver\n* Orlando Rios as Mario\nAdditional voices (Japanese): Nobuyuki Furuta, [[Masato Harada|Masao Harada]], Bin Horikawa, Kazuaki It\u014d, Eriko Kawasaki, [[Akiko Kawase (actress)|Akiko Kawase]], [[Y\u016bto Kazama|Yuto Kazama]], Tsuguo Mogami, [[Mitsuru Ogata]], [[Chiyako Shibahara]], [[Toshitaka Shimizu]], Yoshinori Sonobe, Akiko Takeguchi, Hidenari Umezu, [[Atsuko Yuya]]\n\n==Themes==\nThe film puts an emphasis on the theme of \"coincidences\". Movie critic George Peluranee notes that \"Tokyo Godfathers is a film that shows the small yet significant ties that each of us have with supposed strangers, and tells well the story of miracles, family, love, and forgiveness.\"{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nSusan Napier points out that ''Tokyo Godfathers'' is part of a trend in anime and manga as depicting families in an increasingly dark fashion, showcasing the problems with traditional families, and attempts by people to construct a \"pseudo-family\" out of an increasingly fragmented and isolating modern Japanese society.<ref name=\"Napier\">{{cite book|last1=Napier|first1=Susan|chapter=From Spiritual Fathers to Godfathers|date=2008|publisher=SUNY Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7914-7578-2|pages=33\u201349|title=Imagined Families, Lived Families|editor=Akiko Hashimoto |editor2=John W. Traphagan }}</ref> It is put forth that despite the seeming criticisms of traditional families throughout the film, it ends with a more conservative feeling as everyone returns to their traditional/original families. Despite its seemingly traditional ending, the film offers a more radical version of family. Throughout the story these three homeless vagabonds unknowingly form a \"pseudo-family\" to protect themselves from the outside world and to overcome their personal demons.<ref name=\"Napier\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThis movie was released in North America by [[Sony Pictures]] on December 29, 2003 in an unsuccessful attempt to get an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|for Best Animated Feature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2003-10-30/tokyo-godfathers-theatrical-release|title=Tokyo Godfathers theatrical release|last=Macdonald|first=Christopher|accessdate=December 19, 2019|date=October 30, 2003}}</ref> The movie was released on sub-only DVD on April 13, 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2004-02-23/tokyo-godfathers-on-dvd-april-13th|title=Tokyo Godfathers on DVD April 13th|accessdate=December 19, 2019|date=February 23, 2004}}</ref> and they've planned to use [[DTS (sound system)|DTS]] for the DVD, but was ultimately scrapped.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2004-02-03/tokyo-godfathers-dvd-release|title=Tokyo Godfathers DVD Release|last=Macdonald|first=Christopher|accessdate=December 19, 2019|date=February 3, 2004}}</ref> Announced on December 19, 2019, international animation licensor, [[GKIDS]], released the movie on March 9, 2020 with a brand new 4K restoration and a new English dub.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=GKIDSfilms|number=1207662685007024128|date=December 19, 2019|title=GKIDS is proud to announce the acquisition of the North American theatrical & home video rights to TOKYO GODFATHERS from Satoshi Kon.}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe [[review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 90% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 69 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 7.1/10. The critics consensus states, \"Beautiful and substantive, ''Tokyo Godfathers'' adds a moving \u2013 and somewhat unconventional \u2013 entry to the animated Christmas canon.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tokyo_godfathers |title=Tokyo Godfathers (2020) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 73 out of 100 based on 25 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/tokyo-godfathers |title=Tokyo Godfathers Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three stars out of four calling it 'harrowing and heartwarming' <ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tokyo-godfathers-2004 |title=Tokyo Godfathers | |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Homelessness in Japan]]\n*[[Japanese films of 2003]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ann|film|2018}}\n*{{IMDb title|0388473}}\n*{{Mojo title|tokyogodfathers}}\n*{{Amg movie|296501}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.jmdb.ne.jp/2003/ea003900.htm|title=\u6771\u4eac\u30b4\u30c3\u30c9\u30d5\u30a1\u30fc\u30b6\u30fc\u30ba (''T\u014dky\u014d Goddof\u0101z\u0101zu'')|accessdate=2007-07-21|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Japanese Movie Database]]}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Related topic navboxes|state=collapsed\n|list1=\n{{Satoshi Kon}}\n{{Mainichi Film Award - Animation Film Award}}\n{{Madhouse}}\n{{Tokyo Anime Award for Theatrical Film}}\n{{Three Godfathers}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:2003 anime films]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Animated Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Anime with original screenplays]]\n[[Category:Cross-dressing in film]]\n[[Category:Dentsu]]\n[[Category:Films about homelessness]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Satoshi Kon]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Genco]]\n[[Category:Japanese Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Japanese LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Madhouse (company)]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related animated films]]\n[[Category:Sony Pictures Entertainment Japan films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name          = Tokyo Godfathers\n| image         = Tokyo Godfathers (Movie Poster).jpg\n| caption       = Theatrical release poster\n| director      = [[Satoshi Kon]]\n| producer      = {{Plain list|\n* Shinichi Kobayashi\n* [[Masao Takiyama]]\n* Taro Maki\n}}\n| screenplay    = {{Plain list|\n* [[Keiko Nobumoto]]\n* Satoshi Kon\n}}\n| story         = Satoshi Kon\n| starring      = {{Plain list|\n* [[T\u014dru Emori]]\n* Yoshiaki Umegaki\n* [[Aya Okamoto]]\n}}\n| music         = {{Plain list|\n* [[Keiichi Suzuki (composer)|Keiichi Suzuki]]\n* Moonriders\n}}\n| cinematography = Katsutoshi Sugai\n| editing       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Takeshi Seyama]]\n* Kashiko Kimura\n}}\n| studio        = [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse]]\n| distributor   = [[Sony Pictures Entertainment Japan]]\n| released      = {{Film date|2003|08|30|[[Big Apple Anime Fest]]|2003|11|08|Japan}}\n| runtime       = 92 minutes\n| country       = Japan\n| language      = Japanese\n| budget        = $2.4 million<ref name=\"InterCatsuka\">{{cite web |title=Interview Satoshi Kon |language=French |url=http://www.catsuka.com/focuson.php?id=itw_satoshikon |publisher=Catsuka |date=October 18, 2006 |accessdate=December 20, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross         = $847,106<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web|title=Tokyo Godfathers (2004) - Financial Information |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Tokyo-Godfathers#tab=summary |publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''Tokyo Godfathers'''''|\u6771\u4eac\u30b4\u30c3\u30c9\u30d5\u30a1\u30fc\u30b6\u30fc\u30ba|T\u014dky\u014d Goddof\u0101z\u0101zu}} is a 2003 Japanese [[anime]] holiday, [[Adventure film|adventure]], [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[Satoshi Kon]] loosely based on [[Peter B. Kyne]]'s novel ''[[The Three Godfathers (novel)|Three Godfathers]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hunt|first1=Leon|title=Tauris World Cinema : East Asian Cinemas : Exploring Transnational Connections on Film|date=2010|publisher=I.B Tauris|isbn=9781845116149|pages=122}}</ref>\n\n''Tokyo Godfathers'' was the third animated film directed by Kon and the second which he both wrote and directed. [[Keiko Nobumoto]], noted for being the creator of the ''[[Wolf's Rain]]'' series and a head scriptwriter for ''[[Cowboy Bebop]]'', co-wrote the script with Kon.\n\n''Tokyo Godfathers'' received an Excellence Prize at the 2003 [[Japan Media Arts Festival]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://archive.j-mediaarts.jp/en/festival/2003/animation/works/07an_TOKYO_GOD_FATHERS | title=Excellence Award - TOKYO GOD FATHERS {{!}} Award {{!}} Animation Division {{!}} 2003 [7th] {{!}} Japan Media Arts Festival Archive}}</ref> It also won [[Mainichi Film Award for Best Animation Film|Best Animation Film]] at the 58th [[Mainichi Film Awards]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kon|first=Satoshi|title=The Art of Satoshi Kon|publisher=|others=Tribute from Darren Aronofsky|year=2015|isbn=978-1-61655-741-6|edition=First|location=Milwaukie, OR|pages=142|oclc=896980881}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/mfa/history/058.html|title=\u6bce\u65e5\u6620\u753b\u30b3\u30f3\u30af\u30fc\u30eb \u7b2c58\u56de\uff082003\u5e74\uff09|website=\u6bce\u65e5\u65b0\u805e|language=ja|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nOne Christmas Eve after watching a children's performance of the [[Nativity scene]], three [[Homelessness|homeless]] people \u2013 a middle-aged alcoholic named Gin, a former [[transgender]] [[drag queen]] named Hana, and a dependent teenage [[Runaway (dependent)|runaway]] girl named Miyuki \u2013 discover an abandoned newborn while searching through the garbage. Deposited with the unnamed baby is a note asking the unknown finder to take good care of her and a bag containing clues to the parents' identity. The trio sets out to find the baby's parents. The baby is named {{nihongo|Kiyoko|\u6e05\u5b50}} by Hana, based on the Japanese translation of ''[[Silent Night]]'' literally meaning \"pure child\", as she is found on [[Christmas Eve]]. \n\nOutside a [[cemetery]], the group encounters a high-ranking [[yakuza]] boss trapped under his car. The man happens to know the owner of the club where Kiyoko's mother used to work; his daughter is going to be marrying the club's owner that day. At the wedding reception, the groom tells them that the baby's mother is a former bar girl named Sachiko. He gives them Sachiko's address, but the party is interrupted when a maid, revealed to be a Latin American [[Contract killing|hitman]] in disguise, attempts to shoot the bride's father. The hitman kidnaps Miyuki and baby Kiyoko while holding them hostage at gunpoint and takes them back to his home. There, Miyuki befriends the hitman's wife-(who also has a baby of her own) and shows her some pictures of her family.\n\nHana searches for Miyuki and Kiyoko while Gin takes care of an elderly homeless man who is dying in the street. After giving Gin a little red bag, the old man peacefully passes away. Some teenagers show up and beat up Gin and the dead old man's corpse. Meanwhile, Hana finds the girls and they go off to find a place to stay.\n\nThey go to Angel Tower, Hana's former club where the latter used to work until Hana got fired for attacking an intoxicated customer for insulting her. Gin, who was rescued by another member of the club, is also there. The trio sets out to find Sachiko's house, but they discover that it has been torn down. They are informed of the unhappy relationship between Sachiko and her husband, who is a gambling alcoholic. The group rests at a store until they are told to leave by the clerk. Hana collapses, and is taken by Gin and Miyuki to the hospital. Once at the hospital, Gin finds his estranged daughter, who is also named Kiyoko, working as a nurse. Hana berates Gin in front of his daughter and storms out of the hospital, with Miyuki following behind with baby Kiyoko in hand.\n\nHana and Miyuki find Sachiko about to jump off a bridge. Sachiko insists that her husband got rid of the baby without her knowledge, and that they return the baby to her. Meanwhile, Gin finds Sachiko's husband, who confirms a TV report Gin saw earlier that Kiyoko was actually stolen by Sachiko from the hospital. They chase after Sachiko and Kiyoko. After an intense car chase, Miyuki chases Sachiko to the top of a building. Sachiko reveals she became pregnant in hopes it would bring her closer to her husband. When her baby was [[Stillbirth|stillborn]], she decided to kidnap Kiyoko from the hospital's nursery, thinking, in her grief, the baby was hers. As Sachiko is about to jump off the building intending to commit suicide with Kiyoko in her hands, her husband comes out of his apartment, located just across the street, and begs her to start over with him. Sachiko jumps off nevertheless, but Miyuki manages to catch her before she falls, but then Sachiko accidentally drops Kiyoko. Hana jumps off the building after Kiyoko, catches the baby, and lands safely due to a miraculous gust of wind.\n\nHana, Miyuki, and Gin are taken to the hospital. Miyuki hands Gin his cigarettes and drops the old man's small red bag on the floor, revealing a winning [[lottery]] ticket. Kiyoko's real parents want to ask the trio to become her godparents. When a police inspector introduces them to the trio, the inspector is revealed to be Miyuki's father.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[T\u014dru Emori]] (Japanese) and Jon Avner (English)<ref name=\"engdub\">{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-13/gkids-announces-new-english-dub-cast-for-satoshi-kon-tokyo-godfathers-film/.156415|title=GKIDS Announces New English Dub Cast for Satoshi Kon's Tokyo Godfathers Film|last=Sherman|first=Jennifer|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=February 13, 2020|work=[[Anime News Network]]}}</ref>{{efn|name=animaxdub|In the [[Animax Asia]] release of the film, Gin is voiced by Darren Pleavin, Hana by Russel Wait, and Miyuki by Candice Moore.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/movies/Tokyo-Godfathers/|title=Tokyo Godfathers|website=Behind The Voice Actors|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref>}} as {{nihongo|Gin|\u30ae\u30f3}}; a gambling addict and former bicycle shop owner who claims to have been a bicycle racer. He ran away from his family when his debts became too great. His daughter, a nurse, shares the name of the newfound baby Kiyoko.\n* Yoshiaki Umegaki (Japanese) and [[Shakina Nayfack]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" />{{efn|name=animaxdub}} as {{nihongo|Hana|\u30cf\u30ca}}; a former drag queen who became homeless following the death of a former boyfriend. Hana was also an abandoned child, and is the most sympathetic to Kiyoko's plight and is the one who gives the baby her name.\n* [[Aya Okamoto]] (Japanese) and Victoria Grace (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" />{{efn|name=animaxdub}} as {{nihongo|Miyuki|\u30df\u30e6\u30ad}}; a runaway high school student who fled home following a violent argument with her father.\n*[[Satomi Koorogi]] (Japanese) and [[Kari Wahlgren]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" />{{efn|name=animaxdub}}  as {{nihongo|Kiyoko|\u6e05\u5b50}} an abandoned infant girl that the main characters find in the dumpster on Christmas Eve and decide to reunite her with her parents.\n* [[Sh\u014dz\u014d Iizuka]] (Japanese) and [[Jamieson Price]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as {{nihongo|\u014cta|\u592a\u7530}}; a yakuza boss who the main characters save from being crushed by his car. In gratitude, he invites them to his daughter's wedding reception.\n* [[Seiz\u014d Kat\u014d]] (Japanese) and [[Kate Bornstein]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as {{nihongo|Mother|\u6bcd\u3055\u3093|Kaa-san}}; the proprietor of the [[gay bar]] Hana was formerly employed in.\n* [[Hiroya Ishimaru]] (Japanese) and [[Kirk Thornton]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as {{nihongo|Yasuo|\u6cf0\u7537}}; Sachiko's husband and the one who left Kiyoko at the garbage dump.\n* [[Ry\u016bji Saikachi]] (Japanese) and David Manis (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as an old homeless man who is discovered by Gin. He entrusts Gin with the disposal of a small red bag before passing away.\n* [[Y\u016bsaku Yara]] (Japanese) and [[Crispin Freeman]] (English)<ref name=\"engdub\" /> as Miyuki's father; a policeman in charge of searching for the missing baby Kiyoko, who was separated from her family.\n* [[Ky\u014dko Terase]] as {{nihongo|Sachiko|\u5e78\u5b50}}; a woman who claims to be Kiyoko's mother.\n* [[Mamiko Noto]] as Gin's daughter; a nurse who is also named Kiyoko.\n* [[Satomi K\u014drogi]] as the daughter of the yakuza boss \u014cta, who is also named Kiyoko. \n* [[Akio \u014ctsuka]] as a doctor engaged to Gin's daughter Kiyoko.\n* [[Rikiya Koyama]] as {{nihongo|Arao|\u65b0\u90ce}}; \u014cta's son-in-law who was collecting debt from Gin.\n* [[Inuko Inuyama]] as {{nihongo|Kurumizawa|\u80e1\u6843\u6ca2}}; a resident of Sachiko's former neighborhood.\n* Kanako Yahara as {{nihongo|Yaman\u014dchi|\u5c71\u4e4b\u5185}}\n* Rie Shibata as {{nihongo|Nekobaba|\u732b\u30d0\u30d0}}\n* [[K\u014dichi Yamadera]] as Taxi driver\n* Orlando Rios as Mario\nAdditional voices (Japanese): Nobuyuki Furuta, [[Masato Harada|Masao Harada]], Bin Horikawa, Kazuaki It\u014d, Eriko Kawasaki, [[Akiko Kawase (actress)|Akiko Kawase]], [[Y\u016bto Kazama|Yuto Kazama]], Tsuguo Mogami, [[Mitsuru Ogata]], [[Chiyako Shibahara]], [[Toshitaka Shimizu]], Yoshinori Sonobe, Akiko Takeguchi, Hidenari Umezu, [[Atsuko Yuya]]\n\n==Themes==\nThe film puts an emphasis on the theme of \"coincidences\". Movie critic George Peluranee notes that \"Tokyo Godfathers is a film that shows the small yet significant ties that each of us have with supposed strangers, and tells well the story of miracles, family, love, and forgiveness.\"{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nSusan Napier points out that ''Tokyo Godfathers'' is part of a trend in anime and manga as depicting families in an increasingly dark fashion, showcasing the problems with traditional families, and attempts by people to construct a \"pseudo-family\" out of an increasingly fragmented and isolating modern Japanese society.<ref name=\"Napier\">{{cite book|last1=Napier|first1=Susan|chapter=From Spiritual Fathers to Godfathers|date=2008|publisher=SUNY Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7914-7578-2|pages=33\u201349|title=Imagined Families, Lived Families|editor=Akiko Hashimoto |editor2=John W. Traphagan }}</ref> It is put forth that despite the seeming criticisms of traditional families throughout the film, it ends with a more conservative feeling as everyone returns to their traditional/original families. Despite its seemingly traditional ending, the film offers a more radical version of family. Throughout the story these three homeless vagabonds unknowingly form a \"pseudo-family\" to protect themselves from the outside world and to overcome their personal demons.<ref name=\"Napier\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThis movie was released in North America by [[Sony Pictures]] on December 29, 2003 in an unsuccessful attempt to get an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|for Best Animated Feature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2003-10-30/tokyo-godfathers-theatrical-release|title=Tokyo Godfathers theatrical release|last=Macdonald|first=Christopher|accessdate=December 19, 2019|date=October 30, 2003}}</ref> The movie was released on sub-only DVD on April 13, 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2004-02-23/tokyo-godfathers-on-dvd-april-13th|title=Tokyo Godfathers on DVD April 13th|accessdate=December 19, 2019|date=February 23, 2004}}</ref> and they've planned to use [[DTS (sound system)|DTS]] for the DVD, but was ultimately scrapped.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2004-02-03/tokyo-godfathers-dvd-release|title=Tokyo Godfathers DVD Release|last=Macdonald|first=Christopher|accessdate=December 19, 2019|date=February 3, 2004}}</ref> Announced on December 19, 2019, international animation licensor, [[GKIDS]], released the movie on March 9, 2020 with a brand new 4K restoration and a new English dub.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=GKIDSfilms|number=1207662685007024128|date=December 19, 2019|title=GKIDS is proud to announce the acquisition of the North American theatrical & home video rights to TOKYO GODFATHERS from Satoshi Kon.}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe [[review aggregation]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 90% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 69 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 7.1/10. The critics consensus states, \"Beautiful and substantive, ''Tokyo Godfathers'' adds a moving \u2013 and somewhat unconventional \u2013 entry to the animated Christmas canon.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tokyo_godfathers |title=Tokyo Godfathers (2020) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 73 out of 100 based on 25 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/tokyo-godfathers |title=Tokyo Godfathers Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three stars out of four calling it 'harrowing and heartwarming' <ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tokyo-godfathers-2004s |title=Tokyo Godfathers | |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Homelessness in Japan]]\n*[[Japanese films of 2003]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ann|film|2018}}\n*{{IMDb title|0388473}}\n*{{Mojo title|tokyogodfathers}}\n*{{Amg movie|296501}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.jmdb.ne.jp/2003/ea003900.htm|title=\u6771\u4eac\u30b4\u30c3\u30c9\u30d5\u30a1\u30fc\u30b6\u30fc\u30ba (''T\u014dky\u014d Goddof\u0101z\u0101zu'')|accessdate=2007-07-21|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Japanese Movie Database]]}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Related topic navboxes|state=collapsed\n|list1=\n{{Satoshi Kon}}\n{{Mainichi Film Award - Animation Film Award}}\n{{Madhouse}}\n{{Tokyo Anime Award for Theatrical Film}}\n{{Three Godfathers}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:2003 anime films]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Animated Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Anime with original screenplays]]\n[[Category:Cross-dressing in film]]\n[[Category:Dentsu]]\n[[Category:Films about homelessness]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Satoshi Kon]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Genco]]\n[[Category:Japanese Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Japanese LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Madhouse (company)]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related animated films]]\n[[Category:Sony Pictures Entertainment Japan films]]\n", "name_user": "Alfredsph", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:typp in reference url", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tokyo_Godfathers"}
